28:46.892 --> 28:49.691
<i>...and made him a very rich man.</i>

28:50.312 --> 28:53.486
<i>Rich enough to pursue his real passion:</i>

28:53.649 --> 28:55.322
<i>Solar energy.</i>

28:55.484 --> 28:57.737
<i>Shuman led the team
that designed and built...</i>

28:57.903 --> 29:00.998
<i>...an array of solar energy concentrators.</i>

29:01.156 --> 29:04.126
<i>It could power a steam engine.</i>

29:04.910 --> 29:11.259
<i>Shuman is hoping to use the sun's power
to irrigate the desert and turn it green.</i>

29:11.708 --> 29:15.679
<i>The official inauguration
of Shuman's solar power plant in 1913...</i>

29:15.837 --> 29:17.180
<i>...was a dazzling success.</i>

29:20.842 --> 29:27.566
<i>He had invented a practical way to tap the
sun's energy on an industrial scale...</i>

29:27.724 --> 29:31.354
<i>...making solar energy
even cheaper than coal.</i>

29:33.605 --> 29:36.279
<i>The British and German governments
both offered Shuman...</i>

29:36.441 --> 29:39.695
<i>...generous funding to
develop his invention.</i>

29:39.861 --> 29:44.162
<i>It was the ideal source
of abundant power in tropical regions...</i>

29:44.324 --> 29:47.874
<i>...where imported coal
was prohibitively expensive.</i>

29:48.036 --> 29:51.882
<i>But Shuman was dreaming even bigger.</i>

29:52.040 --> 29:54.042
<i>In a letter to Scientific American...</i>

29:54.209 --> 29:56.928
<i>...he calculated that his
solar power plants...</i>

29:57.087 --> 30:01.558
<i>...if deployed in an area of the Sahara
Desert only 150 miles on a side...</i>

30:01.717 --> 30:06.974
<i>...could supply as much power as consumed
by all the industries of the world.</i>

30:07.180 --> 30:08.523
<i>But it was not to be.</i>

30:08.974 --> 30:12.023
<i>The market for a liquid fossil fuel,
petroleum...</i>

30:12.185 --> 30:16.065
<i>...was exploding for shipping,
home heating, cars and trucks.</i>

30:16.231 --> 30:19.235
<i>Oil was abundant, cheaper even than coal...</i>

30:19.401 --> 30:22.075
<i>...and much easier
to get out of the ground and process.</i>

30:22.237 --> 30:25.992
<i>It took 100 men a week
to fuel a ship with coal...</i>

30:26.575 --> 30:30.205
<i>...but with oil one man could do the job
in a single day.</i>

30:31.246 --> 30:34.250
<i>A year after Shuman's triumph
in the desert...</i>

30:34.416 --> 30:36.339
<i>...World War I broke out.</i>

30:36.501 --> 30:39.971
<i>His solar collectors were recycled
into weapons.</i>

30:40.130 --> 30:43.555
<i>Frank Shuman's dream
of a solar-powered civilization...</i>

30:43.717 --> 30:47.938
<i>...would have to wait another century
before it was reborn.</i>

30:49.431 --> 30:54.733
<i>There's another inexhaustible
source of clean energy for the world.</i>

30:55.187 --> 30:57.940
<i>The winds themselves are solar powered...</i>

30:58.106 --> 31:02.782
<i>...because our star drives the winds
and the waves.</i>

31:02.944 --> 31:04.571
<i>Unlike solar collectors...</i>

31:04.738 --> 31:07.617
<i>...wind farms take up very little land...</i>

31:07.783 --> 31:12.459
<i>...and none at all if offshore,
where the winds are strongest.</i>

31:12.996 --> 31:15.920
<i>If we could tap
even 1 percent of their power...</i>

31:16.083 --> 31:19.633
<i>...we'd have enough energy
to run our civilization.</i>

31:32.307 --> 31:35.481
And more solar energy falls
on the Earth in one hour...

31:35.644 --> 31:39.615
...than all the energy our civilization
consumes in an entire year.

31:39.773 --> 31:43.528
If we could harness a tiny fraction
of the available solar and wind power...

31:43.693 --> 31:46.742
...we could supply
all our energy needs forever...

31:46.905 --> 31:50.375
...and without adding any carbon
to the atmosphere.

31:58.834 --> 32:00.586
<i>It's not too late.</i>

32:00.752 --> 32:03.005
<i>There's a future worth fighting for.</i>

32:03.171 --> 32:04.297
<i>How do I know?</i>

32:04.464 --> 32:08.014
<i>Every one of us
comes from a long line of survivors.</i>

32:08.176 --> 32:10.929
<i>Our species is nothing, if not adaptive.</i>

32:11.096 --> 32:14.316
<i>It was only because our ancestors
learned to think long-term...</i>

32:14.474 --> 32:17.193
<i>...and act accordingly
that we're here at all.</i>

32:17.352 --> 32:19.320
<i>We've had our backs to the wall before...</i>

32:19.479 --> 32:23.029
<i>...and we came through
to scale new heights.</i>

32:23.191 --> 32:26.536
<i>In fact, the most mythic
human accomplishments of all...</i>

32:26.695 --> 32:29.323
<i>...came out of our darkest hour.</i>

32:38.707 --> 32:40.175
<i><font color="#808080">TYSON :</font>
Once there was a world...</i>

32:40.333 --> 32:44.634
<i>...rigged with 60,000
hair-triggered nuclear weapons.</i>

32:44.796 --> 32:48.892
<i>The combatants were the two most
powerful countries on earth.</i>

32:49.050 --> 32:51.519
<i>And they were locked in a deadly embrace...</i>

32:51.678 --> 32:55.649
<i>...each vowing that they would rather see
everything we love destroyed...</i>

32:55.807 --> 32:58.731
<i>...than submit to the will of the other.</i>

32:58.894 --> 33:02.740
<i>When I was 3 years old the largest
man-made explosion of all time...</i>

33:02.898 --> 33:06.072
<i>...was detonated by the Soviet Union.</i>

33:08.904 --> 33:12.909
<i>That terror has subsided
to be replaced by new fears.</i>

33:13.074 --> 33:17.045
<i>The danger that the 2000 largest cities
on earth would be reduced to rubble...</i>

33:17.204 --> 33:21.425
<i>...in the space of an afternoon
is no longer one of them.</i>

33:22.125 --> 33:25.720
<i>The nuclear rivalry between the
United States and the Soviet Union...</i>

33:26.546 --> 33:29.015
<i>...had another byproduct.</i>

